</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,816,1152,1218]" box="[151,816,1152,1218]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis box="[151,242,1152,1177]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Biology</emphasis>
Hosts are unknown. Adults were collected in March.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1272,1418]" box="[151,275,1272,1297]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis box="[151,275,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1272,1418]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
This new species was treated as Var. C of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hope" authorityYear="1833" box="[704,882,1312,1337]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Uracanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[704,882,1312,1337]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">U. triangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lea, A. M." box="[928,1063,1312,1338]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="272 - 436" refId="ref76262" refString="Lea, A. M. (1916) Notes on some miscellaneous Coleoptera with descriptions of new species, Part II. Transactions of the Royal Society of South Australia, 40, 272 - 436." type="journal article" year="1916">Lea (1916)</bibRefCitation>
. It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Thongphak &amp; Wang, 2007" authorityName="Thongphak &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2007" box="[1228,1386,1312,1337]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Uracanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1228,1386,1312,1337]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">U. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but differs in having the pubescence on the elytral disc more or less even; elytral apex more deeply emarginate, and sutural apical spine longer.
</paragraph>
